UML:TaggedValue.value: Purpose: Describe how the system is divided into different subsystems or components, and how these are related to form a coherent whole. Input: Requirements view Output: UML class diagram The system decomposition model describes how the target system is divided into different subsystems or components, and how these are related to form a coherent whole. This includes how subsystems or components in the target system relate to subsystems or components in other systems. A modularised description of the system facilitates reuse of well-defined components and identifies points of integration with other systems. Decomposition of the system will usually be applied hierarchically, with the initial diagram showing an overview of the whole system. Further decomposition of subsystems is performed when this is seen as part of the architecture, while decomposition of more fine grained components are typically considered as detailed design and not handled in the AD. In cases where a subsystem is particularly large, complex, or independent on the rest of the system, an alternative is to create a separate, complete AD for the subsystem. As part of the decomposition model, the components are also related to their tier in the reference architecture. Decomposition models can be created for all of the tiers in the reference model, but usually at least the business service and user service tiers are described in this model.
See the Document Management diagram for more details on the modelling approach.

This diagram is used to add direct realization of interfaces for components. This is a workaround to enable messages that are realized by the components through the interfaces of their ports to be used when creating sequence diagrams.
  • Use the class diagram called "__notation workaround" in your building block
  • Add each component to this diagram (select "as simple links" in the dialog that appears when dragging the component into the diagram)
  • Add each interface provided by a port of the component to the diagram
  • Add a realization connector from the component to each of the interfaces provided by one of its ports
  • For composite components, also add realization connector from the composite to interfaces delegated to its required ports

This diagram describes the decomposition of one building block.
  • The interfaces used should be created in the same package, and you can initially add create them in this diagram.
  • Interfaces should consist of a logical group of operations, corresponding e.g. to a Java interface or to a set of uAAL services.
  • Attach the interfaces to the ports by selecting addRequiredInterface of addProvidedInterface under the Embedded Elements entry of the context menu. Use a single interface per port.
  • Use dependency connectors to connect required to provided interfaces
  • Use delegate connectors to delegate from or to ports of the building block
